	    The announcement came on Radio Tehran just before the 2 pm news. It was that a 'fatwa' or decree from Ayatollah Khomeini, the revered spiritual leader of Iran's 50 million Shia Muslims.<p>'In the name of God the Almighty,' he intoned an announcer. 'There is only one God, to whom we shall all return. I would like to inform all the intrepid Muslims in the world that the author of the book 'The Satanic Verses', which has been compiled, printed and published in opposition to Islam, the Prophet and the koran, as well as those publishers who were aware of its contents, have been sentenced to death.<p>I call on all zealous Muslims to execute them quickly, wherever they may find them, so that no one will dare to insult the Muslim sanctions. Whoever is killed on this path will be regarded a martyr, God willing.<p>In Addition, anyone who has access to the author of the book, but does not have the power to execute him, should refer him to the people so that he may be punished for his actions. May God's blessing be on you all. Ruhollah Musavi Khomeini.'<p>And so began one of the most chilling episodes to engulf the world of culture in recent times. It encompassed a myriad of complexities: Two great religions, Islam and Christianity; secularism versus religious orthodoxy; artistic freedom versus state power; pluralism and tolerance versus doctrinal certainty.<p>Even yesterday's statement of regret from Salman Rushdie, still in hiding, seemed only to deepen and confound the crisis. There were clear signs of serious disagreement in Tehran over how to handle the escalating controversy, apparently signalling an unseemly tussle between the various factions in the revolutionary government.<p>But the two main characters in this complex and tragic drama remained somehow apart from the action.<p>On one side of the stage stood the commanding figure of the Ayatollah, an ageing cleric who had spearheaded a revolution. On the other side, Salman Rushdie, a Westernised, Muslim born writer who wrestles with some of the most profound issues of our times: the nature of good and evil, the concept of 'revealed literature' as opposed to 'imagined literature', the making of history and the birth of great historical ideals.<p>Rushdie sees questions and ambiguities ('Doubt, it seems to me, is the central condition of the human being in the twentieth century'); Khomeini sees only certainties. The author probes and explores, plays with ideas, exploits the realms of dreams and fantasy, the cleric demands obedience to the law, with no room for doubt or question. They may both have been born into the Islamic world, but they have moved far into opposite directions, so that they face each other across the yawning divide of alien cultures. <p>And then, of course, there is politics. Khomeini's revolution is in trouble, with the war against Iraq ended but not won, and a bitter struggle underway in Tehran between the 'pragmatists' and the 'radicals' over whom will inherit the Ayatollah's mantle when he dies. Iran has few friends in the Arab world, where antipathy towards the Persians combines with suspicion of revolution and historic antagonisms between the Sunni and Shia branches of Islam. A crusade- or perhaps jihad is a better word- against blasphemy is a good way to unite the Islamic world.<p>'The Satanic Verses' was launched with a publisher's party late last September in an elegant house in Chelsea. The novel has been shortlisted for the Booker prize, and Viking, the publishers were hoping for extensive press coverage. Two weeks later the book won the Whitbread prize for fiction. Amid the euphoria, the publishers should probably have paid more attention to a letter received from Harley Street dentist Hesham El Essawy, chairman of the Islamic Society for the Promotion of Religious Tolerance. After having read Rushdie's novel, he wrote on October 12 to say that he regarded it as an insult to Islam.<p>'I would like to invite you to take some kind of corrective stand, before the monster you have so needlessly created grows, as it will do worldwide, into something uncontrollable,' he wrote. It was to prove a horribly prophetic warning. But at the time, Viking's reaction was astonishment that an organisation ostensibly formed to promote 'tolerance' should be asking a publisher to act as a censor. El Essawy says now that he merely wanted an insertion of an apology.<p><b>Blasphemy</b><p>The early complaints went unheeded. Groups of offended Muslims met to decide how to proceed. One idea was to have the book prosecuted for blasphemy; a top London solicitors, Kingsley Napley were consulted, but were advised that the law applied only to Christianity. (A decade ago, Mary Whitehouse successfully prosecuted the newspaper Gay News after it published a poem suggesting that Christ had a homosexual fantasy about a Roman Centurion while on the cross.)<p>Muslims across Britain were warned about the book by religious leaders. If it was not blasphemous under English law, it was, they said, under Islamic law. It was decided to set up an action committee, based at the Islamic Cultural Centre in London's Regent's Park mosque, the largest in the country. India, Pakistan and South Africa had banned the book within a few weeks of publication, but the book was still being imported into many other Muslim countries. So on the 27 October, the Action Committee wrote to all Muslim ambassadors in London calling for a ban on the book. Among the recipients was Mr Ahkunzadeh Basti the Iranian charge d'affaires. <p>After several weeks of behind the scenes activity , it seemed to the increasingly frustrated Muslim campaigners that they had still failed to get their message across. A solicitor in the north of England suggested that if they really wanted was publicity, they could always try burning the book in public; there was he pointed out, no law against that.<p>So on 2 December, 7,000 Muslims in Bolton staged a demonstration and set light to a copy of 'The Satanic Verses'. 'It was a peaceful protest, and we burned the book to try and attract public attention,' said the Bolton Action Committee supporter Mr Ismael Lorgat. The national press ignored them.<p>The frustration increased. On 14 January, Muslims in Bradford repeated the book burning exercise, and this time, the press were on hand. At last, their fury had been heard.<p>As the uproar grew - in the United States, the American publishers received 100,000 letters of protes, even before the book was officially published - one man, Ayatollah Khomeini, remained silent. Then, last Sunday six Muslims were shot dead by police during a demonstration against the book in front of the American Information Centre in Islamabad.<p>It was this - the spectre of Muslims dying while, at least in his eyes, protecting the faith from blasphemous insult - that finally spurred the Iranian leader into action. Increasingly marginalised as his country's more pragmatic leaders opened up relations with the West, which he regards as a source of all that is evil, Khomeini needed only a few short well timed sentences to place himself beack in the centre of stage. Once again, he had taken on his old role as defender of the whole Islamic world against Western, imperialist and American plots. <p>Yet his appeal to 'all Muslims' was theologically questionable. Khomeini has no authority over the majority of the world's Muslims, including the vast majority in Britain who are Sunnis and not Shias and do not recognise his spiritual leadership.<p>Even among Shias, Khomeini is only one of six leading Ayatollahs, none of whom, significantly, has so far echoed Khomeini's death sentence against Rushdie.<p>Despite the almost ritual protestations of support from other Islamic spokesmen, there were plenty of signs that his grimly specific threat had caused considerable unease.In Cairo, seat of the most authoritative interpreters of Sunni Islam, said there was no tradition in Islam of executing people without trial. Other leading spokesmen spoke of the need for appraisal of a work before reaching such conclusions, rather than the piecemeal excerpts, taken out of context, which had been circulated to Muslims around the world. <p>Even in Tehran, there were some indications by Friday that the political leadership might be looking for ways out of the furore. President Khamenei suggested an apology from Rushdie might be enough to get him off the hook; two days previously he had called for the author's 'revolutionary execution'. Last night it looked as if the 'pragmatists' had regained control of the situation, and then as if they had lost it again.<p>Hints of a moderating of the hard-line had been accumulating since Friday, when the Iranian charge in London seemed to be trying to distance the political leadership from what he called the 'purely religious' edict issued by the Ayatollah. 'This opinion does not imply any political gesture by Iran nor does it imply any interference in the internal affairs of your country with which we have diplomatic relations,' he said on Channel 4 news. 'It is a purely religious statement and I am very surprised this statement has been misinterpreted in your country.'<p>Whatever the religious leaders in Iran may have been saying, it was clear that Tehran's diplomatic corps were anxious to minimise the damage done by Khomeini's pronouncement. And in London, too, while public outrage was only too evident, the foreign office appeared desparate to keep communications open with Tehran.<p>A Foreign Office spokesman said that the Government was proceeding on the basis that Iran is 'a revolutionary country and that considerable confusion exists in its government.'<p>It is hard to imagine such an understanding attitude if a similar edict had been issued in, for example, Libya and Syria, two nations with whom Britain has broken off all diplomatic relations. But Britain and Iran have traditionally enjoyed something of a special relationship, and even at the worst of times - in 1979 when the American hostages were seized in Tehran and again in 1987, when British diplomat Edward Chaplin was beaten up by Revolutionary Guards - we have never wholly severed our ties.<p>In Bradford, which boasts 22 mosques (only two of them Shia), there was both a genuine outrage and deep unease last week at the way in which the controversy had exploded. Parvez Akhtar, a financial adviser in his thirties who works for the local company, said, 'Morally, as a human being, I know it is wrong, but if Rushdie came here he would be torn to pieces. He is a dead man.'<p>He admitted: 'I haven't read the book and I don't want to. From the extracts I have seen it is grossly insulting to the Prophet and our religion. Islam preaches peace, but when it is insulted we have a jihad- a holy war. We know what the consequences could be, but for some people here Islam comes before family, even before one's life.'<p>Leaders of the city's 60,000 Muslim faced the thankless task of reconciling the belief of many of their followers that Rushdie should be punished with their fear of serious damage to previously good race relations.<p>In his office in the house where the composer Delius was born, Sher Azram, president of the city's council for Mosques, warned: 'As a result of publication of this book, we are going to have an extremely difficult job in promoting harmony.<p>'We don't object to criticism, but we do object to blatant insult. We objected to the publishers, then to local MPs, to the Home Secretary and finally the Prime Minister. We have petitions signed by thousands of people, yet we have received not a single positive response.<p>'Why is it that the law in this country gives protection to Christianity but not to Islam? Is that justice? In Pakistan many hundreds of people have been injured, several have been killed because of this book. Someone is responsible, so should they not be punished?<p>Salman Rushdie has already been punished - for the crime of daring to tackle questions about the nature of religion at a time when fundamentalism has a hold over many millions of people. He was forced into hiding, under armed guard, for fear of his life. Yesterday he expressed his 'profound regret' at the distress that his book had caused. But he did not apologise for having written the book in the first place.<p>Rushdie has dared, deliberately, to provoke, not so as to make mischief or to insult, but as an artist. 'Any writer wishes to provoke the imagination,' he said in an interview with Channel 4's Bandung File last week. 'You want to make people think about what you're writing.'<p>In an article in this newspaper last month, he wrote: 'Literature is where I go to explore the highest and lowest places in human society and the human spirit, where I hope to find not absolute truth but the truth of the tale, of the imagination and of the heart.<p>'The battle over 'The Satanic Verses' is a clash of faiths, in a way. Or, more precisely, it's a clash of languages. As my fictional character Salman says of my fictional prophet Mahound, "It's his Word against mine."'
    </div>

    

		
		
            	    





		
										

        

			            						
					
					
                                                                                                                                                                                                                            

                                                                        
	
	
		
			
                                                        
